-- ds.h1: Different types of Coffee 

- Espresso: Espresso is a concentrated form of coffee made by forcing hot water under high pressure through finely ground coffee beans. It has a strong flavor, rich crema (a layer of foam on top), and is the foundation for many other coffee-based drinks.
- Cappuccino: Cappuccino is made by combining equal parts of espresso, steamed milk, and milk foam. It is typically served in a small cup and often garnished with cocoa or cinnamon on top.
- Latte: A latte is similar to a cappuccino but has more steamed milk and less foam. It is made with a shot of espresso topped with steamed milk, and it can be flavored with syrups such as vanilla or caramel.
- Americano: An Americano is made by diluting a shot of espresso with hot water. It has a similar strength to traditional brewed coffee but with a different flavor profile.
- Macchiato: There are two types of macchiatos: espresso macchiato and latte macchiato. An espresso macchiato is a shot of espresso "stained" with a small amount of milk. A latte macchiato, on the other hand, is made by pouring steamed milk over a shot of espresso. 


These are just a few examples of the many types of coffee available. Each type offers a unique taste experience, allowing coffee enthusiasts to explore and find their preferred flavors and preparations.

